{{nihongo|'''Tokiwa Jinja'''|常磐神社}} is a [[Shinto shrine]] adjacent to the [[Japanese gardens|gardens]] of [[Kairakuen]] in [[Mito, Ibaraki]], Japan. Founded in 1874, enshrined are [[Tokugawa Mitsukuni]], second ''[[daimyō]]'' of the [[Mito Domain]] and compiler of [[Dai Nihonshi]], and [[Tokugawa Nariaki]], ninth lord and founder of the nearby [[Kōdōkan]] [[han school]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://komonsan.jp/for_english/tokiwa_jinja_shrine.html |title=Tokiwa Jinja Shrine |publisher=Tokiwa Jinja |accessdate=19 May 2011 |archive-date=6 June 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140606182014/http://komonsan.jp/for_english/tokiwa_jinja_shrine.html |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.city.mito.lg.jp/html/english/spots/tokiwa.htm |title=Tokiwa Shrine |publisher=[[Mito, Ibaraki|Mito City]] |accessdate=19 May 2011}}</ref> In 1882 the shrine joined the ranks of the {{nihongo|''bekkaku kanpeisha''|別格官幣社}} or [[Modern system of ranked Shinto Shrines|Imperial Shrines]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/entry.php?entryID=1092 |title=Encyclopedia of Shinto – Modern shrine ranking system |publisher=[[Kokugakuin University]] |accessdate=19 May 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://eos.kokugakuin.ac.jp/modules/xwords/images/uploads/EOS070712Eb.pdf |title=List of kanpeisha |publisher=[[Kokugakuin University]] |accessdate=19 May 2011}}</ref> The Tokiwa Jinja Reisai or [[Japanese festivals|annual festival]] is held on 12 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tobunken.go.jp/english/events/5-e.html |title=List of Annual Events – May |publisher=[[National Research Institute for Cultural Properties, Tokyo]] |accessdate=19 May 2011}}</ref> A cannon and a drum have been designated as [[Cultural Properties of Japan|Cultural Properties]] by the city.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.city.mito.lg.jp/view.rbz?nd=1379&of=1&ik=1&pnp=1373&pnp=1374&pnp=1379&cd=1479 |title=Mito bunkazai |publisher=[[Mito, Ibaraki|Mito City]] |accessdate=19 